That same logic extended to the treatment of state governments. California\'92s resistance to federal immigration raids and troop deployments drew a direct threat from the president to withhold $40 billion in wildfire relief. In Michigan, the administration invoked a national energy emergency to order two coal plants to remain open despite state law requiring a shift to clean energy and despite local opposition. In both cases, the message was that access to federal resources and regulatory deference depended on political obedience. The law still existed on paper. Its application became contingent on a state\'92s standing with the White House.\
