Protest rights came under similar pressure. The \'93No Kings\'94 demonstrations brought at least five million people into the streets in more than 2,000 events, many of them festive and explicitly patriotic, with flags, references to the Constitution, and invocations of the American Revolution. Yet in Los Angeles, police declared an \'93unlawful assembly,\'94 used teargas and foam bullets, and enforced a curfew after protesters shouted at marines guarding a federal building. The district attorney filed felony assault and firearms charges against some demonstrators, even as federal prosecutors pursued their own cases. In Salt Lake City, a peacekeeper\'92s attempt to disarm an armed man at a protest ended in a fatal shooting of another demonstrator. The scene showed how quickly a charged environment can turn deadly.\
