Beneath these confrontations lay a deeper reordering of citizenship. On the very day of Trump\'92s second inauguration, an executive order attempted to cancel birthright citizenship for children of undocumented immigrants, a direct challenge to the Fourteenth Amendment. That order was tied up in litigation and now sat before the Supreme Court, but its existence signaled a willingness to redraw the constitutional map of who is \'93in.\'94 At the same time, the administration considered adding 36 countries, including 25 in Africa, to the travel ban, and moved to require foreign students and scholars to unlock their social\uc0\u8209 media accounts for consular review. The stated goal was to screen for hostility to the United States and its allies, especially Israel. The effect was to make online speech a condition of educational opportunity.\
